## WEEK 2: FORMAL LOGIC, INFERENCE & PROOFS

### Core Concepts

**Formal Logic:**
- When we say logic is "formal" it means: **arguments in logic have rigour** + **a conclusion is acceptable based only on the form of the argument**
- NOT about what domain the argument pertains to — form is all that matters!

**Knowledge Base (KB):**
- A KB = **a set of sentences all of which are accepted to be true** + **a set of premises or axioms**
- NOT "basic knowledge to study CS" or "what Homo sapiens possess"

**Entailment:**
- Entailment = stating that a sentence α **is necessarily true** given a KB
- NOT "possibly true" — entailment is about logical necessity

**Proof:**
- A proof in logic involves the **use of rules of inference on a given KB**
- Also: **a syntactic process devoid of truth values of sentences** AND **devoid of meaning of sentences**
- Proofs are purely mechanical/syntactic — they don't care about what symbols mean

**Soundness & Completeness:**

| Property | Definition |
|----------|-----------|
| **Sound** | Can derive **only true sentences** + Cannot derive **any false sentence** |
| **Complete** | Can derive **all true sentences** |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> A **sound** logic machine: derives ONLY true sentences, cannot derive ANY false sentence.  
> A **complete** logic machine: can derive ALL true sentences.

**Valid Rule of Inference:**
- Is the basis of **deductive inference**
- Is based on a **tautological implication**
- Is a **sound rule** of inference

**Atomic Sentences in Propositional Logic (PL):**
- Must be **declarative** (true or false)
- Examples: "The giraffe is a vegetable" ✅, "The Moon is larger than the Sun" ✅
- NOT: "Please pass the ketchup" (imperative), "This sentence is false" (paradox), "What did Biden say?" (question)

### Assignment 2 — Detailed Q&A

**Q1: "When we say that logic is formal, we mean that":**
> **Answer:** Arguments in logic have rigour + A conclusion is acceptable based only on the form of the argument
> **Why:** "Formal" = about the FORM, not the content/domain.

**Q2: "By a knowledge base (KB) we mean":**
> **Answer:** A set of sentences all of which are accepted to be true + A set of premises or axioms
> **Why:** KB is our "ground truth" — the starting assumptions we reason from.

**Q3: "Entailment entails":**
> **Answer:** Stating that a sentence α is **necessarily true** given a KB
> **Why:** Entailment (⊨) means logical consequence — necessarily true, not just possibly.

**Q4: "A proof in logic":**
> **Answer:** Involves the use of rules of inference on a given KB + Involves a syntactic process devoid of truth values + Involves a syntactic process devoid of meaning
> **Why:** Proofs are syntactic manipulation — they work on symbols regardless of meaning.

**Q5: "A sound logic machine":**
> **Answer:** It can derive only true sentences + It cannot derive any false sentence
> **Why:** Soundness = no false positives. Everything derived is actually true.

**Q6: "A complete logic machine":**
> **Answer:** It can derive all true sentences
> **Why:** Completeness = no false negatives. Every truth is derivable.

**Q7: "A valid rule of inference":**
> **Answer:** Is the basis of a deductive inference + Is based on a tautological implication + Is a sound rule of inference
> **Why:** Valid rules guarantee truth-preservation (soundness) based on tautologies.

**Q8: "Atomic sentences in PL":**
> **Answer:** "The giraffe is a vegetable" + "The Moon is larger than the Sun"
> **Why:** Both are declarative (can be T or F). "Please pass the ketchup" is imperative; "This sentence is false" is paradoxical.

**Q9: "If Amogh ran for 21km then he would be tired / Amogh is not tired / Therefore, he did not run for 21km":**
> **Answer:** Y (Valid — this is Modus Tollens!)
> **Why:** p⊃q, ¬q ⊢ ¬p. If running→tired, not tired → not running. Classic Modus Tollens.

**Q10: "If the tea were to be cold then Shashank will not drink it / Shashank did not drink the tea / Therefore, the tea was cold":**
> **Answer:** N (Invalid — this is Affirming the Consequent fallacy!)
> **Why:** p⊃¬q, ¬q ⊬ p. Just because he didn't drink doesn't mean it was cold (could have other reasons).

### Practice Assignment 2 — Key Questions

**Atomic sentences in PL:**
- "The sky is blue and the day is sunny" — uses connective AND, NOT atomic (uses one connective)
- "The ant is black" — YES, atomic
- "The ant is red" — YES, atomic
- "The document is in London or Paris or Rome" — uses connective OR, NOT atomic

**Boolean connectives:** AND (∧), OR (∨), IMPLIES (⊃), EQUIVALENCE (≡)

**Commutative connectives:** AND (∧) and OR (∨) — NOT IMPLIES!
- a ∧ b = b ∧ a ✅
- a ∨ b = b ∨ a ✅
- a ⊃ b ≠ b ⊃ a ❌

**Associative connectives:** AND (∧), OR (∨), EQUIVALENCE (≡)

**Truth Table for P ⊃ Q (MEMORIZE THIS!):**

| P | Q | P ⊃ Q |
|---|---|-------|
| T | T | **T** |
| T | F | **F** ← Only FALSE case! |
| F | T | **T** |
| F | F | **T** |

> [!CAUTION]
> **P ⊃ Q is FALSE only when P is TRUE and Q is FALSE.** This is the single most important truth table entry!

**With P: "Simba is a lion" and Q: "Simba eats meat":**
- P⊃Q means: "If Simba is a lion then Simba eats meat" / "Simba is not a lion or Simba eats meat"

**Tautology check:** (P ⊃ (Q ⊃ R)) ⊃ ((P ⊃ Q) ⊃ (P ⊃ R)): **YES**, this is a tautology!

**Equivalence: P ≡ Q = (P ⊃ Q) ∧ (Q ⊃ P)**
Also: (¬P ∨ Q) ∧ (P ∨ ¬Q)

**Expression ((P ∧ Q ∧ R) ⊃ S) = P ⊃ (Q ⊃ (R ⊃ S))** — currying / exportation law

**Conditional (P ⊃ Q) can be read as:**
- P implies Q ✅
- if P then Q ✅
- P only if Q ✅
- Q if P ✅
- Q provided that P ✅
- P is a **sufficient** condition for Q ✅
- Q is a **necessary** condition for P ✅

**Binary connectives between P and Q:** There are **16** possible binary connectives (2^(2^2) = 16)

