## WEEK 3: PROPOSITIONAL LOGIC — TABLEAUX, MODELS & NATURAL DEDUCTION

### Core Concepts

**Well-formed Formulas (WFFs) of PL:**
- Atomic propositions (P, Q, R) are WFFs
- (P ∧ Q) ⊃ R ✅ — WFF
- (P ∧ Q ⊃ S) ✅ — WFF
- P ∧ S ❌ — only if properly parenthesized

**Derivation from KB:**
- Given KB = {P ∨ ¬R, (R ∧ T), (W ⊃ S), ((P ∧ S) ⊃ Q), (T ⊃ ¬S)}: can derive P, ¬S, ¬W

**The Deduction Theorem:**
- If one can prove β given α, this means that (α ⊃ β) can be derived
- This connects proof-theoretic notion with semantic notion

**Derived Rule of Inference:**
- Is a rule that may or may not be sound
- Can be added to existing rules **without any loss of correctness**
- Can help in **reducing the length of some proofs**

**Model:**
- A model for a set of statements S = a valuation for the atomic propositions that makes **all the sentences in S true**

**Tableau Method:**

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Key Tableau Rules:**
> - Eliminating a connective results in **further branching for some connectives** AND **linear extension for some connectives**
> - ∧ (AND): **linear** expansion — extends the same branch
> - ∨ (OR): **branching** expansion — creates two new branches  
> - ⊃ (IMPLIES): **branching** (¬α | β)
> - ¬∨: **linear** expansion
> - ¬∧: **branching** expansion

**Tableau Method — Satisfiability/Unsatisfiability:**
- At least one branch should be a model for the KB to be **satisfiable**
- All branches must be closed for the KB to be **unsatisfiable**
- If no branch of the tableau being constructed for a formula is closed → it is **satisfiable**

**Tableau Properties:**
- Each branch is an **interpretation** of the KB
- A branch can be closed with some binary connectives remaining
- It is possible to have a KB where: there is only one linear branch, every node has exactly one child, there are no linear extensions (every node has exactly two children), there are no extensions (no children)

### Assignment 3 — Detailed Q&A

**Q1: Which are sentences of PL? (atomic set {P, Q, R, S})**
> **Answer:** (P ∧ Q) ⊃ R, (P ∧ Q ⊃ R)
