## WEEK 4: FIRST-ORDER LOGIC (FOL)

### Core Concepts — DEEP DIVE

**Why FOL over PL?**
- PL can't express relationships between objects
- PL can't express generality ("all", "some")
- FOL adds: **variables, quantifiers (∀, ∃), predicates, functions, constants**

**FOL Language Components L(P, F, C):**
- **P** = set of predicate symbols (properties/relations)
- **F** = set of function symbols (maps objects to objects)
- **C** = set of constant symbols (named objects)

**Terms in FOL:**
- Constants (Sneha, Jack, 5)
- Variables (x, y, z)
- Function applications: father(x), mother(Sneha), f(g(x))

**Atomic Formula:** Predicate applied to terms: P(t1, t2, ..., tn)
- Example: Loves(John, Mary), Tall(father(x))

**Sentences vs Formulas:**
- A **sentence** has NO free variables (every variable is bound by a quantifier)
- A **formula** may have free variables

**Quantifiers:**
- **∀x** (for all x): Universal — statement holds for every object in the domain
- **∃x** (there exists x): Existential — at least one object satisfies the condition

**Interpretation I = ⟨D, {.}⟩:**
- D = domain (set of objects)
- {.} = mapping from symbols to domain elements/relations/functions

**Unification:**
- Process of finding substitutions that make two expressions identical
- Unifiable: {P(x, a)} and {P(b, a)} with substitution {x/b}
- NOT unifiable: {P(a, x)} and {P(b, y)} (constants a≠b clash)

**Skolemization:**
- Removes ∃ quantifiers by replacing existential variables with:
  - **Skolem constants** (when not inside any ∀): ∃x P(x) → P(sk1)
  - **Skolem functions** of enclosing ∀ variables: ∀x ∃y P(x,y) → P(x, f(x))

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Skolem constant** = like a constant (maps to fixed element) + like a variable (mapping is unspecified) + DIFFERENT from variable because you can't determine its value by inference
>
> **Skolem function of variable y** means x was existentially quantified in the scope of universally quantified y

**Modified Modus Ponens = Modus Ponens + Universal Instantiation**

### Assignment 4 — Complete Q&A with Reasoning

**Q1: First-order logic refers to elements in domain using:**
> **Answer:** Using constant symbols + Using variable symbols + Using functions defined in the language
> **Why:** Constants name specific objects, variables range over objects, functions map to objects. "Maintaining a registry" is NOT an FOL concept. "Predicates defined in language" describe properties, don't refer to elements.

**Q2: When we define a predicate RichMan and have RichMan(suresh), we assert:**
> **Answer:** RichMan is some subset of a domain D
> **Why:** A predicate defines a SET of objects that satisfy it. RichMan(suresh) means Suresh ∈ {x | RichMan(x)}, and this set is a subset of D.

**Q3: An atomic formula in FOL:**
> **Answer:** Is a well-formed formula + Is the smallest unit that can have a truth value assigned to it
> **Why:** Atomic formulas like P(x) are the building blocks. They don't have connectives (so not "all logical connectives") and they can't have only unary connective (that would be ¬P(x) which isn't atomic).

**Q4: A variable x in an FOL formula ω:**
> **Answer:** Must necessarily be in the scope of a quantifier if ω is a sentence + Can occur in the scope of more than one quantifier
> **Why:** In a SENTENCE (closed formula), all variables must be quantified. A variable like x in ∀x∃y P(x,y) is in scope of ∀x. Variables CAN appear in nested quantifier scopes. But x CAN also be a constant symbol of language (that's different).

**Q5: Which are sentences of FOL? (father, coach = functions; Tall = relation; Sneha = constant)**
> **Answer:** Tall(father(x)) — NOT a sentence (x is free!), Tall(father(Sneha)) ✅, ∀y(Tall(father(Sneha))) ✅, ∃x(Tall(father(x))) ✅, ∀y(Tall(father(x)) ⊃ Tall(x)) — NOT a sentence (x is free!)
> **Why:** A sentence requires ALL variables to be bound. Tall(father(Sneha)) has no variables → sentence. ∃x(Tall(father(x))) → x is bound → sentence.

**Q6: Sentences of FOL with equality:**
> **Answer:** father(Sneha) = coach(Sneha) ✅, ∃x(father(Sneha) = coach(x)) ✅, ∃x(father(Sneha) = coach(Sneha)) ✅, ∃x(father(x) = coach(x)) ✅, ∀x(father(Sneha) = coach(x)) ✅, ∀x(father(x) = coach(x)) ✅
> **Why:** All variables are bound by quantifiers, and equality between terms is valid FOL.

**Q7: Interpretation I determines truth value of:**
> **Answer:** Formulas with terms only from F and C + Formulas with terms made up of free variables and constants
> **Why:** An interpretation assigns meanings to constants and functions, but free variables need a variable assignment too. Actually, the interpretation + variable assignment together determine truth.

**Q8: Which pairs of clauses are unifiable?**
> **Answer:** {*Likes(*Z₂, anisa)}, {Likes(*Z₂, anisa)} ✅ — identical! {*Likes(*Z₂, X₁)}, {Likes(*Z₂, mother(*Z₂))} ✅ — X₁ → mother(*Z₂). {*Likes(*Z₂, X₁)}, {Likes(*Z₂, mother(anisa))} ✅ — X₁ → mother(anisa)
> **Why:** Unification fails when constants clash or occurs check fails (x = f(x) → infinite loop).

**Q9: Modified Modus Ponens combines:**
> **Answer:** Modus Ponens and Universal Instantiation
> **Why:** Regular MP: from P and P⊃Q derive Q. Modified MP first universally instantiates ∀x(P(x)⊃Q(x)) to P(a)⊃Q(a), then applies MP.

**Q10: A Skolem constant:**
> **Answer:** Is like a constant (maps to fixed element in domain D) + Is like a variable (mapping to element is not specified) + Is different from a variable (value cannot be determined by inference)
> **Why:** Skolem constants are "witnesses" for existential claims — we know something exists but we don't know exactly which element.

**Q11: If variable x is a Skolem function of variable y:**
> **Answer:** x is existentially quantified in the scope of y which is universally quantified
> **Why:** ∀y ∃x P(x,y) → P(f(y), y). The existential x depends on the universal y, so its witness is a FUNCTION of y.

### FOL Representation Patterns — THE GOLDEN RULES

> [!CAUTION]
> **THE #1 EXAM TRAP: "All" vs "Some" representation**
> 
> | English | FOL | Connector |
> |---------|-----|-----------|
> | "All X are Y" | ∀x (X(x) **⊃** Y(x)) | IMPLICATION |
> | "Some X are Y" | ∃x (X(x) **∧** Y(x)) | CONJUNCTION |
> | "No X are Y" | ∀x (X(x) **⊃** ¬Y(x)) | IMPLICATION + NEG |
> | "Only X are Y" | ∀x (Y(x) **⊃** X(x)) | REVERSED IMPLICATION |
> 
> **WHY "All" uses ⊃ and not ∧:**  
> ∀x (Apple(x) ∧ Red(x)) means "EVERYTHING is an apple AND red" — WRONG!  
> ∀x (Apple(x) ⊃ Red(x)) means "IF something is an apple THEN it is red" — CORRECT!
> 
> **WHY "Some" uses ∧ and not ⊃:**  
> ∃x (Apple(x) ⊃ Red(x)) is trivially true (any non-apple satisfies it) — TOO WEAK!  
> ∃x (Apple(x) ∧ Red(x)) means "there exists something that IS an apple AND IS red" — CORRECT!

