### Common Exam Traps to AVOID

> [!WARNING]
> **Trap 1:** ∀x(Apple(x) ∧ Red(x)) ≠ "All apples are red" — this says EVERYTHING is a red apple!  
> **Trap 2:** ∃x(Apple(x) ⊃ Red(x)) is trivially true — ANY non-apple makes it true!  
> **Trap 3:** Resolution DOES NOT always terminate in FOL  
> **Trap 4:** SLD Resolution DOES NOT always terminate  
> **Trap 5:** NOT all FOL formulas can be expressed as Horn Clauses  
> **Trap 6:** Sound ≠ Complete (they are independent properties!)  
> **Trap 7:** ¬∀x P(x) ≡ ∃x ¬P(x) (NOT ∀x ¬P(x)!)  
> **Trap 8:** Strict inheritance means CANNOT override (not "can")  
> **Trap 9:** Credulous extensions are individually consistent, but different ones may disagree  
> **Trap 10:** Frame Problem = what stays the SAME, not what changes

### Speed Solving Techniques

1. **For "All/Some" FOL questions:** Just remember All→⊃, Some→∧. Done in 5 seconds.
2. **For DL questions:** Convert to FOL mentally: ⊑ = ⊃, ⊓ = ∧, ⊔ = ∨
3. **For CD theory:** Ask "Does it involve transfer? Physical movement? Mental info? Eating?" → maps directly to ATRANS/PTRANS/MTRANS/INGEST
4. **For Resolution:** Always negate the goal first! If you get □, it's proved.
5. **For Validity questions (Y/N):** Check if the argument form is: p⊃q, ¬q ⊢ ¬p (Modus Tollens = Y) vs p⊃q, ¬q... does it follow? Check truth table.
6. **For Prolog tracing:** Go top-down, left-to-right, match rules in order, backtrack on failure.
7. **For Event Calculus:** Draw a timeline! Mark when actions happen, what they initiate/terminate.
8. **For Default Logic:** Apply each default: check if prerequisite known AND justification consistent.

